Coming to the dream that you saw, I would say it was a ver=
y significant dream. =C2=A0Snakes in dreams can have various meanings. Not =
all are good. But this one seems to me like a indication of a very specific=
 kind of spiritual expeirence to come, or would have come to you, had you n=
ot made any change =C2=A0in your routine sadhana.=C2=A0
Spirituality has tw=
o parts. We start off with a desire to experience God, we do whatever we th=
ink can help us in that, which can lead to experiences which tell us we may=
be come a bit closer. Then comes digesting them. To do so one has to have a=
 stable mental and emotional condition.
From what you described my sanguine=
 feeling is that a strong experience was coming your way, but doubt and fea=
r stopped it and made it recede back. Now spiritual experiences are not lik=
e daily states of consciousness. If they were, they would be no good. They =
are different. And that came make us feel unnerved at times.
Did this happe=
n due to homa? I think it was destined for you at some point. It could as w=
ell have happened one early morning as you were having a cup of tea without=
 lifting a finger. What sadhana does - by which I mean homa, japa, yoga wha=
tever - is change the patterns of karma and accelerate the experiences that=
 would have come to you anyway. But more than that it helps your mind-body =
to stabilize which is vital to be able to integrate and digest an experienc=
e when it comes.=C2=A0
So without thinking about it I would suggest that yo=
u keep doing sadhana, whatever it maybe. As you do more, you nervous system=
 will grow stronger, your emotional, and mental sheath with become calmer a=
nd stabler and maybe the next time the Snake comes you won't feel unnerved!=
 -:)
Wish you all the best.
